column12: IMPROVEMENTS RELATING TO WHEEL MOUNTED BRAKING DISCS
Floating carrier retention for a planetary gearset
column13: A planetary gear system within a vehicle wheel has a sun gear at the wheel axis driven by a fluid motor and further includes a ring gear secured to the wheel rim. Planet gears, engaging both the sun gear and ring gear, are mounted on a carrier which is revolvable as the planet gears orbit around the sun gear while transmitting drive from the motor to the wheel with a speed reduction and a corresponding torque amplification. The carrier is not tightly restrained in either the radial or axial direction enabling positional self-adjustment to relieve stress concentrations at gear teeth. Limits for the axial and radial play of the floating carrier are fixed by positioner means defining an annular groove into which the radially innermost edge of the carrier is loosely received, thrust bearing means such as thrust pins or annular thrust rings being situated within the groove at each side of the carrier edge. Situating the positioner means at the minimum diameter portion of the carrier minimizes friction, wear, power dissipation and heating as that portion of the carrier turns at a smaller velocity than the more outward portions of the carrier.

28,475. Campbell, J. S. Dec. 24. Locks, key; fastenings.-A lock, suitable for boxes, drawers, cabinets, portmanteaus, bags, cigar and cigarette cases, purses, &c., is so arranged that it may be converted into an ordinary spring-push fastening. Figs. 4 and 5 show a lock suitable for a desk, despatch box, jewel case, cabinet, &c. A tube a is provided with a flange to engage a shoulder in a socket e or an adjustable tube s secured within the socket e, and has also an internal flange, which acts as a seat for a slotted disc, plate, or dummy keyhole d. Within the tube a is a tube b closed at the top by a plug k, which is slotted or perforated to form a keyhole. Within the tube b is located a push tube or rod c. The inner ends of the tubes a, b, c lie flush with the base-plate f, and the tubes a, b are retained in the socket by means of a pivoted latch l or other suitable means. A spring catch m, pivoted to the plate f, is formed with a latch piece o to engage the hasp or striking plate o<1>. This catch is guided by a pin p, but can be turned out of the way when it is desired to withdraw the tubes. To release the catch, a key g, Fig. 12, is inserted in the dummy keyhole d, which is turned until it is brought into line with the keyhole in the tube b. The key is passed through these holes, and is employed to push down the tube c, which presses the catch out of engagement with the plate o<1>. By turning the latch l out of engagement with the tubes a, b, the device is converted into a fastening, and can be operated by pressing down the tube a. The tubes may be withdrawn readily to enable the tube provided with the keyhole plug k to be changed. This plug may be formed in a cap provided with steps to engage corresponding steps in the tube b, so that the cap may be changed without changing the tube. Instead of the flange on the tube a and the engaging shoulder in the socket e or tube s, the tubes a, b may be formed at the bottom with flanges to engage a guide-pin, and the latch l adapted to enter a slot in the tubes to retain them within the socket. In another arrangement, the tube c is dispensed with, and the key acts directly upon the catch. The tube a carries the dummy keyhole at the top, and carries at the lower end a plate perforated to form the actual keyhole.

1,148,646. X-ray micro-analyser. CAMBRIDGE INSTRUMENT CO. Ltd. 13 Feb., 1968 [16 Feb., 1967], No. 7462/67. Heading H5R. In a micro-analyser, a finely focused electron beam impinges on the surface of a specimen, the X-rays so produced are detected by at least 3 separate crystal or grating spectrometers, the electron beam is scanned along a datum line on the specimen, and spectrometers are arranged around the specimen such that the plane of each spectrometer, that is the plane defined by the directions of the incident and reflected X-ray beams, contains a line which is perpendicular both to the datum line and to the path of the rays incident on that spectrometer. Preferably the spectrometers are arranged symmetrically on each side of the plane containing the axis of the electron beam and the datum line. Two or more of the spectrometers may be arranged such that they have a common privileged plane, that is a plane perpendicular to the spectrometer plane and containing the direction of the incident beam. The spectrometers may have the same angle between the specimen surface and the incident ray. The spectrometers may also be arranged symmetrically about a plane that contains the mid-point of the line scanned on the surface of the specimen by the electron beam and is perpendicular to the datum line. During the analysis the specimen itself may be moved in a direction perpendicular to the datum line.

column12: Palladium salts of condensed phosphoric acid
column13: Palladium metal is obtained from palladium salts of a condensed phosphoric acid by reduction with hydrogen in aqueous suspension.ALSO:Palladium salts of a condensed phosphoric acid having a polymerization number of from 2-14 are prepared by heating a halide, nitrate or sulphate of palladium and the condensed phosphoric acid or a precursor thereof, for example ammonium salts or hydrated monomeric acids such as orthophosphoric acid. The salts may be reduced to palladium suitable for use as a catalyst with hydrogen in aqueous suspension. The salts may be used as catalyst in a process for producing hydrogen peroxide by contacting hydrogen and oxygen in the presence of liquid water. The hydrogen peroxide may be used directly for an oxidation process or the catalyst may be separated and the resulting solution evaporated.

column12: Power resistor having insulation regions defining a tortuous current path
column13: An improved power resistor includes a resistive element extending between a first electrical connection terminal and a second electrical connection terminal. The resistive element has a plurality of first insulating regions, arranged along its length extending generally parallel to each other in a first row. The resistive element further has a plurality of second insulating regions arranged generally parallel to each other in a second row. The first and second rows are further arranged generally parallel to each other so that each of the second insulating regions extends between two of the first insulating regions. The first and second insulating regions thereby define a tortuous current path from the first terminal to the second terminal. This tortuous path creates a current path between the terminals having increased resistance. The insulating regions are preferably interleaved chevrons and are preferably formed by stamping out portions of a resistive slab, made of steel or the like. The slab may be rolled or bent to form part of a resistor assembly.

column13: A fault-current-limiting circuit to be used in combination with a poly-phase circuit is disclosed. The poly-phase circuit comprises a plurality of inductive windings each having a first terminal connected to a common point. At least one of the windings has a second terminal connected to an electrical load. The fault-current-limiting circuit comprises first and second electrical paths between the common point and ground. The first electrical path comprises a current-limiting device having a first state whereat current passes through the device and a second state whereat current substantially does not pass through the device. The device switches from the first state to the second state when current through the device exceeds a pre-determined maximum. The second path has an electrical resistance significantly greater than a resistance of the first path when the device is in the first state.

A felt or similar ring 15<x> carried between flanges 15 and 15<a> on a sleeve 15<b>, rotatably secured to each tube 8 by compressing the sleeve 15<b> into a depression formed in the tube 8, renders the shaft noiseless. In a modification, the flexible shaft consists of a wire coil carried either in an india-rubber tube which fits in the handle-bar, or by india-rubber washers secured on the shaft. To secure the brake in its active or inactive position, a spring pawl 16 is mounted in a slot 1<x> formed in the handle 1 so as to engage a ratchet-wheel 18 concealed under the handle. A tooth 16<b>, Fig. 5, on the pawl 16 engag the ordinary ratchet teeth and secures the brake in its action. The brake is secured in its inactive position by the pawl engaging a depression 17 in the wheel 18. Pressure on the rear end of the pawl 16 releases the brake. The pawl 16 may be provided with a screw 19, as shown in Fig. 8, in order to lock it on the wheel 18. This screw may be shaped so that a special key is required to turn it, thereby preventing theft.

Machine pour le nettoyage ou le décapage de fils ou de tiges métalliques
System and Method for Normalized Focal Length Profiling
column13: A system and method are provided for normalizing a camera focal length. A perspective geometry estimator accepts a scanned image from a camera having an undefined focal length, and generates a normalized focal length estimate for the image. The normalized focal length estimate is compared to a normalized focal length density distribution. If the normalized focal length estimate meets a minimum threshold of probability, the normalized focal length estimate is selected and the image is processed using the selected normalized focal length estimate. If the normalized focal length estimate fails to meet the minimum threshold of probability, the image is processed using the highest probability prior normalized focal length from the normalized focal length density distribution.
